environmental hazards is profoundly shaped by environmental health scientists’ efforts to address the structural vulnerabilities of their field. She then takes up the political effects of this research, both from the perspective of those who seek to establish genomic technologies as a new basis for environmental regulation, and from the perspective of environmental justice activists, who are concerned that that their efforts to redress the social, political, and economical inequalities that put people at risk of environmental exposure will be undermined by molecular explanations of environmental health and illness. Exposed Science thus offers critically important new ways of understanding and engaging with the emergence of gene-environment interaction as a focal concern of environmental health science, policy-making, and activism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aEnvironmental healthxPolitical aspects. 0aHealth risk assessment. 0aPollution. 7aHEALTH & FITNESS / Health Care Issues.2bisacsh  a20th century.  aengaging.  aenvironmental hazards.  aenvironmental health sciences.  aenvironmental health scientists.  aenvironmental justice activists.  aenvironmental regulation.  aethnographic observation.  aexperiments.  agene environment interactions.  agenomic technologies.  ahealth policy.  ahistory of medicine.  ahuman condition.  ain depth interviews.  amedical.  amedicine.  apage turner.  apolitical effects.  apopulation health.  apublic policy.  ascience and technology.  ascientists.  astructural vulnerabilities.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052027517140uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052095524040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520955240423Coveruhttps://ww